subsection.p:
We have now seen two forms for linear equations: the general linear form,
\blert{Ax + By = C}
and the form for a linear model,
\blert{y = (\text{starting value}) + (\text{rate}) \times t}
It is sometimes useful to convert an equation from one form to the other.

li.p:
We first isolate the y-term on one side of the equation.

                4x-3y \amp = 6 \amp\amp \bluetext{\text{Subtract }4x\text{ from both sides.}} 
                -3y \amp = 6 -4x\amp\amp \bluetext{\text{Divide both sides by } {-3}.} 
                \frac{-3y}{-3} \amp = \frac{6-4x}{-3} \amp\amp \bluetext{\text{Simplify: divide each term by  }{-3}.} 
                y \amp -2 + \frac{4}{3}x
